
Building Alternatives: A Macro Philosophy for Anti-Oppressive Social Work



Building Alternatives: A Macro Philosophy for Anti-Oppressive Social Work
When Numbing Crumbles
I was glad the Week 8 video had little new information. The course prepared me well—I recognized the patterns, understood the structures. But I still cried when learning that 215 Indigenous children were discovered buried at Kamloops Residential School, a number that grew to over 750 at Cowessess when sonar investigations expanded (Cultural Survival, 2021). Even though I am born and raised in modernity and white supremacy, the structures of numbing and rationalizing are crumbling in my being. This crumbling has been helped by work I have been doing outside the academy: participating in discussion groups on Vanessa Andreotti’s (2021) Outgrowing Modernity and engaging with Bayo Akomolafe’s (2024) writing on post-activism. The tears are evidence that something is shifting—not just cognitively, but somatically.
Settler Colonialism Is Not Structural Racism
Karina Walters, Choctaw Nation member on the panel, described the NASW report as lighting a sacred fire—a covenant requiring constant tending. She warned that when truth-telling is replaced by performance, “it brings sickness to everybody” (NASW, 2021). What reframed everything for me was her insistence that the discovery of those children’s bodies is not about structural racism—it is about settler colonialism, and the two are not the same. Structural racism is a mechanism of settler colonialism. Eliminating racism does not eliminate the colonial structure underneath (NASW, 2021).
This distinction matters for how we think about macro practice. If we only fight racism without questioning the colonial logic beneath it—the logic of land theft, labor extraction, and who gets to define knowledge—we are reforming a system designed to oppress. Akomolafe (2024) calls this post-activism: our responses to crisis may reproduce the very conditions we are trying to escape. Colonialism has a shape—it centers itself, narrates itself as necessary, and defines the terms of its own critique. When we discuss oppression exclusively within social work’s own journals and frameworks, we reproduce that shape, as if the field that perpetuated harm is best-positioned to diagnose the cure.
A Macro Philosophy: Building Alternatives
Corley and Young (2018) argue that cultural competence “inherently validates and preserves the status quo.” The challenge, then, is how to move beyond individual interventions and tackle institutional reform. My macro philosophy is this: nothing macro starts macro. Every structural transformation begins with someone building something different.
Dettlaff et al. (2020) argue the child welfare system “is a system that needs to be broken” (p. 500)—a system that removes Black children at 77% higher rates even with identical risk (p. 507). I agree with the diagnosis. But I think the path forward looks like what Marsha Linehan did with psychiatric institutionalization. Linehan experienced institutional harm firsthand—electroconvulsive therapy, seclusion, restraint that worsened rather than healed her (Linehan, 2020). She did not campaign for dismantling psychiatric hospitals. She built an alternative. DBT kept people in their communities. Her research showed psychiatric crisis services may actually produce iatrogenic harm (Coyle et al., 2018). She changed the system by creating something that made the old model unnecessary. The evidence did the dismantling.
Build what Dettlaff et al. describe: universal supports, community-based care designed by communities (p. 510). And in education, build pedagogies that work at the level of embodiment, not just cognition. This is where social work’s self-centering becomes visible as a colonial pattern. Social work reproduces colonialism’s shape when it teaches anti-oppression exclusively through social work authors analyzing social work, within social work institutions, for social work students. The discipline that participated in Japanese American internment, Indigenous child removal, and the eugenics movement is now the discipline that teaches students to critique those very histories—without stepping outside its own epistemological enclosure to do so. This self-referencing is not neutral. It is the colonial logic of self-centering reproduced at the level of curriculum.
Andreotti’s Facing Human Wrongs course offers a model for something different: body/land recalibration practices, forest walks, artistic engagement alongside academic texts—pedagogy designed to help students hold heavy content in their bodies rather than only their minds. I entered that course invested in reading. I left it understanding that embodied engagement was what actually opened space to see colonial structures operating in my own being. The shift did not come from a better argument. It came from a different way of being in relationship with what I was learning.
I would encourage UNE to consider this: expand anti-oppression curricula beyond social work authors to include education scholars like Andreotti, philosophers like Akomolafe, and activists whose knowledge is produced through practice and relationship rather than peer review. Break the self-centering pattern by letting other disciplines, other epistemologies, other ways of knowing into the room. Walters said social work is at a point of great power and she hopes we use it wisely (NASW, 2021). Using it wisely might mean changing not just what we teach but how we sit with what we already know.

