Self-Reflection, Evaluation, and Growth Plan




From Savior to Student: My Journey Through Anti-Oppression Social Work

I can say this course moved me in a lot of ways. A lot of ways to be a social worker crossed my mind and thoughts of practices as being colonial or decolonial spiralled in my awareness. I began this MSW program thinking I would build a private practice serving white middle-class upscale women. Now, I feel ambiguous about how this can be perpetrating racism as the mental health system alienates oppressed populations for various reasons. I am also aware that for white people to go "save the world" is just colonialism with a social work degree (Asher BlackDeer & Gandarilla Ocampo, 2022).
This paper examines my journey of understanding anti-oppression social work over the past seven weeks. I reflect on the types of individuals I might find particularly challenging, stimulating, and beneficial to work with given my background, values, and relationship style. I identify my areas of privilege and complicity, and I outline concrete steps I will take moving forward. Chapman and Withers (2019) ask: "How, then, do we work for a better, more just world when we know that so many before us thought they were doing good but were causing harm?" (p. 356). This paper is my attempt to sit with that question without easy answers.

My Journey: Understanding What I Didn't Know
When I entered this program, I had what I would call an ambiguous view of social work—I knew there was a double-edged sword, helping alongside harm. But I didn't have the dimension of the problem. Seven weeks of coursework systematically dismantled my assumptions:
Week 1: My IAT results showed implicit bias I didn't know I carried. Week 2: Jane Addams endorsed eugenicists while being celebrated as a founder. Week 3: Social workers staffed Japanese American internment camps and called it "the greatest planned migration" (UHGCSW, 2020). Week 4: Rehabilitation forces disabled people to conform to abled norms rather than building inclusive systems. Week 5: Assimilation policies removed 20% of the Mexican population from the US, with social workers facilitating it. Week 6: Even when Black and white children have identical income and identical assessed risk, Black children are removed from their homes at 77% higher rates—that's not a broken system, it's racism (Dettlaff et al., 2020, p. 507).

Each week dismantled another piece of the story I had about what social work was and who I would be as a social worker.

By Week 6, I thought the answer was to go work directly with the communities most impacted—to do child welfare work, to learn from minoritized communities. Then I read Asher BlackDeer and Gandarilla Ocampo (2022), who write that "field placement...continues to send mainly white students into communities of color for the purposes of learning, often treating the community as guinea pigs in the pursuit of white knowledge" (p. 720). They document how "students may lack investment in the agency or work, have wanting experience and skills, or have generally problematic behavior" which impacts vulnerable individuals who "may have no choice...but to accept subpar service" (p. 730).

My impulse to "help" was still centering myself. I was imagining myself learning at the expense of communities already bearing massive trauma. That's not anti-oppression—that's reproducing the pattern.

Concrete Actions During This Course

This course gave me vocabulary to name what I couldn't name before. I can call racism racism now. I can name colonialism. I can have courageous conversations I avoided before.

During this course, I left my meditation school—the Arcane School, where I'd been studying for seven years. I'd paused the curriculum multiple times because something felt wrong, something circling around colonialism and whose wisdom counted as legitimate. But I couldn't name it clearly. During this course, I finally could: their teachings were racist. I left.

I also sent a community project proposal to our local library for courses on AI and creativity (originally developed for recursive.eco). The library's initial feedback was enthusiastic. We're now planning quarterly study group meetings where my four AI courses will serve as conversation starters. This feels different from saviorism—I'm building something in my own community, offering tools rather than positioning myself as needed by others.

I've also been able to set boundaries with my parents about policing my daughter's body. They make comments about how she eats, about being "too thin," comparing bodies. I told them I don't want bodily comments around her. I can connect this now to my own anorexic episodes as a teenager—those were probably related to the same policing mechanisms. When we frame some lives as morally superior to others, even white people get oppressed by that system. We fear that if we don't fit the mold, we won't have value (Chapman & Withers, 2019).

My Identities: Privilege and Entanglement

I am Brazilian and attend Umbanda, an Afro-Brazilian religious practice that honors caboclos (indigenous spirits) and Preto Velhos (spirits of enslaved Africans). This positions me as someone who values non-Western healing practices and understands how dominant systems exclude traditional approaches.

But I also hold significant privilege. I am white or white-passing, which grants me access and safety that people of color don't have. I have educational privilege—I'm pursuing a graduate degree. I have economic privilege—my family in Brazil employs a nanny who has worked for them for 35 years. I have language privilege—even though English isn't my native language, I have access to tools like AI that help me write with courage, reducing barriers others face.

The nanny relationship particularly troubles me. She's part of my family's household, providing essential care, yet hasn't been able to afford to buy a house after 35 years of work. I could help with a down payment but haven't acted. This is what Chapman and Withers (2019) call being "complicit in these systems" even while recognizing they're unjust (p. 357).

Regarding field education specifically, Asher BlackDeer and Gandarilla Ocampo (2022) identify how "white students harming marginalized communities for the sake of learning" is built into social work training (p. 735). If I were to do practicum in child welfare or with communities of color, I would be yet another white student learning at their expense. Field instructors often "avoid or hesitate discussions of diversity and identity" and take "color-evasive approaches," which gaslights students of color and reinforces oppression (p. 729-730). Even if I imagine myself as different, as "aware," the structure itself creates harm.

Types of Clients: Challenging, Stimulating, and Beneficial

Clients I might find challenging are those who would mirror my own privilege and complicity back to me. Wealthy white clients who expect me to validate their worldview without questioning systems that benefit them. Clients who want therapy to be comfortable rather than transformative. People who expect me to have all the answers, positioning me as expert rather than collaborative partner. These would challenge me because they might trigger my own desire for comfort, my own resistance to staying in the discomfort of complicity.

Clients I would find stimulating are those exploring different ways of healing and being. People interested in creativity as processing tool—art, tarot, journaling as ways to reframe thoughts and cope with cultural norms through symbols. Couples navigating perpetual conflicts where the work isn't solving differences but building relationships that can hold them. People from diverse cultural backgrounds who bring healing practices from their traditions. Those questioning dominant narratives about what healing should look like.

My AI and creativity work could be particularly relevant here. I'm both deeply concerned about AI and enthusiastic about its potential to decrease oppression. AI has given me courage to write in English, which isn't my native language—this is itself a form of barrier reduction. Projects using AI for creativity, tarot readings for journaling, processing through symbols—these could offer accessible tools for people to explore their experiences outside traditional therapy models.

Clients I would benefit from working with are those who would call out my biases and blind spots. People who wouldn't let me center myself or my comfort. Communities that would require me to continually educate myself rather than expecting them to educate me. People who understand their own healing better than I ever could, who need me to get out of the way rather than impose frameworks. Clients who would remind me constantly that I don't have answers, only responsibility to show up and do my work.

Jung said you always need to see the human in front of you above all else—not the diagnosis, not the protocol, not the theory. I want to practice that way: client-centered, trauma-informed, without letting my academic, technical, and racial biases become the structure of my work.

The Valley Between Fear and Certainty

Chapman and Withers (2019) write that social justice workers can get "caught up in the fear they'll cause harm that they never do anything concrete" or be "so certain of their righteousness that they act without reflecting upon their actual effects" (p. 357). Both extremes are destructive.

The valley between these polarities is what Vanessa Andreotti calls acting from responsibility rather than heroism. She writes about the need to "shed individual arrogance and narcissism, and see ourselves as 'cute and pathetic in this enormity'" (as cited in What Could Possibly Go Right?, 2020). Not acting from certainty that we're saving anyone. Not paralyzed by fear of causing harm. But showing up with humility, acknowledging we're complicit, doing our work to reduce harm while knowing we'll likely perpetuate some harm anyway.

For me, this valley looks like: acknowledging I'm not neutral and won't be. Recognizing my biases clearly. Building alternatives rather than positioning myself as needed by communities already bearing trauma. Acting in my own communities rather than going to "help" others. Offering tools (like AI creativity groups) rather than expertise. Being willing to be corrected, to be told I'm wrong, to change course.

Future Steps: Building Alternatives, Not Saving

I see myself in private practice doing pro bono community work. Not because I'm needed to save anyone, but because that's where I can contribute without centering myself as savior. Professor Randall's feedback helped me understand I don't need to write off private practice—meaningful anti-oppression work can happen there while staying actively involved in social justice.

The library AI study group is one concrete alternative I'm building. Rather than going into communities that don't need me, I'm creating something in my own community. Using my four courses on AI and creativity as conversation starters for quarterly meetings. Offering tools that could reduce barriers—language access, creative processing, journaling through tarot and symbols. This isn't positioning me as expert rescuing people. It's building infrastructure for people to explore their own experiences.

My recursive.eco platform follows similar logic. I built it free because I see poor families as victims of predatory technology. It's tiny, doesn't address root causes. But it reduces immediate harm without requiring people to be grateful to me for it. It's building alternatives rather than demanding credit for helping.

Moving forward, I commit to:

Educating myself rather than expecting oppressed groups to educate me. Reading work by BIPOC scholars, disabled scholars, queer scholars. Following their lead rather than centering my comfort.

Staying present with discomfort. When I want a charitable interpretation, when I want to believe reform rather than abolition, when my comfort is threatened—those are moments to pause and ask who my comfort serves.

Building inclusive practice that recognizes certain bodies already carry massive trauma from systemic violence. Not approaching difference as problem requiring solution. Not imposing frameworks that assume white middle-class nuclear families as normative.

Acknowledging complicity without paralysis. I'm entangled in oppressive systems. I benefit from them. The work isn't extracting myself but inhabiting these entanglements differently—acting from responsibility not heroism, building alternatives not demanding recognition.

Continuing concrete actions. The library group. Pro bono work. Boundaries with family about body policing. Leaving spaces that perpetuate harm. Speaking up about racism when I see it.

I don't have all the answers. Chapman and Withers (2019) don't provide them either—they end by asking questions, not offering solutions. What I have is grief about the harm social work has caused. Responsibility to do my work. Commitment to building alternatives rather than positioning myself as needed. Humility about how much I still don't understand.

The NASW Code of Ethics (2021) calls social workers to challenge social injustice. If that commitment means anything for me, it means listening to communities most harmed. It means building capacity in my own communities. It means recognizing that I'm not the hero of this story—I'm just someone trying to show up responsibly in systems I can't step outside of.



