Week 6 Reflective Journal: Sitting With the Dimension of the Problem



What I Thought I Knew
Before this course, I had what I'd call an ambiguous view of social work—similar to how I think about the Jesuits. I knew there was a double-edged sword: liberation theology alongside colonization, helping alongside harm. I knew racism was a problem in social work. I'd read about it abstractly. But I didn't have the dimension of the problem.
Six Weeks of Innocence Breaking
It wasn't just the 77% statistic, though that was devastating—learning that even when Black and white children have identical income and identical assessed risk, Black children are removed from their homes at 77% higher rates (Rivaux et al., 2008, as cited in Dettlaff et al., 2020). That demolished my search for explanations other than racism.
But it's been every week. Every assignment has broken a little more of the innocence I had that I could be a savior.
Week 1: Learning my IAT results showed implicit bias I didn't know I carried.
Week 2: Reading about Jane Addams endorsing eugenicists while being celebrated as a founder.
Week 3: Watching symposium videos documenting how social workers staffed intake teams for Japanese American internment and called it "the greatest planned and controlled migration" (UHGCSW, 2020).
Week 4: Understanding that rehabilitation isn't benevolent—it's forcing disabled people to conform to abled norms.
Week 5: Realizing assimilation policies removed 20% of the Mexican population in the US, with social workers facilitating it.
Week 6: The 77% child welfare statistic. The CSWE acknowledging social workers "rescued" Indigenous children from poverty created by colonization itself (CSWE, n.d.).
Each week dismantled another piece of the story I had about what social work was and what I would be doing.
Who Am I Without Saviorism?
This is the question I'm sitting with now. If I'm not here to save anyone, who am I? Just somebody who needs to cope with grief.
Vanessa Andreotti writes about this shift—moving from "the responsibility towards making us become the heroes of the new system" to "responsibility towards those who are coming next" (as cited in McConnell Foundation, 2022). Not acting from arrogance but from responsibility. She talks about the need to "shed individual arrogance and narcissism, and see ourselves as 'cute and pathetic in this enormity of what's going on'" (as cited in What Could Possibly Go Right?, 2020). That's where I am. Grieving the hero story I didn't realize I was carrying.
What's Shifting
I came into this program thinking about building a private practice. Working with couples, which I love (still theoretically). Maybe charging what the market will bear—I've heard $200 per session, which is top-notch if I end up going back to Brazil.
Now I'm questioning: do I really want to be another white middle-class woman therapist serving white middle-class women? Adding to the oversaturation of services for privileged populations while Black and Brown communities have the least access to care? And would the care I would be providing just another facet of colonialism, or ableism?
I keep thinking about my recursive.eco project. I built it free because I think poor families are victims of predatory technology. It's tiny. It doesn't address root causes. But maybe that's one way to give back—building tools that reduce immediate harm while being honest they're not solutions. Maybe doing pro bono work. Maybe organizing rather than just providing services. I don't know yet. But I can't imagine charging $200/hour exclusively to people who look like me and calling that social justice work.
Sitting With Grief and Responsibility
Chapman and Withers (2019) ask how we hold responsibility to challenge oppression while recognizing we're complicit in these systems. They don't provide easy answers. Neither do I have them.
What I'm learning is that the grief matters. Andreotti teaches that we need to shed arrogance—the arrogance of thinking we can fix, the arrogance of saviorism, the arrogance of certainty. What's left is responsibility without heroism. Action without solutions. Showing up without knowing.
The NASW Code of Ethics (2021) says social workers should challenge social injustice. But NASW itself has been complicit in racist systems. So maybe I listen instead to the communities most harmed by social work—Black families, Indigenous families, disabled people, poor people.
And maybe I keep attending to my discomfort. When I want to look away, when I want a charitable interpretation, when I want to believe reform rather than abolition—those are the moments to pause and ask: who does my comfort serve?


