Allyship as Process, Implication, and Practice





Self-Examination and Critical Reflection on Identity
My social identity is marked by simultaneous privilege and oppression, which complicates any simple understanding of my positionality as an aspiring ally. I am a white, upper-middle-class woman, raised in a single-family home, currently in a heterosexual marriage, and I identify with the gender I was assigned at birth. These identities afford me significant structural advantages in the United States, particularly in terms of safety, institutional access, and credibility within professional spaces. At the same time, I am a Brazilian immigrant, a woman, and someone who has been perceived by some in the U.S. as a person of color, depending on context. These identities expose me to forms of marginalization, precarity, and fear—particularly in the current political climate, where immigration policies and rhetoric have intensified. My husband is not a U.S. citizen, which heightens my awareness of how fragile safety and belonging can be, even as I recognize that I remain privileged relative to many immigrant families.
Following Waters’ (2010) framing of allyhood as a developmental process, I do not understand allyship as a stable identity one “achieves,” but rather as a set of evolving practices shaped by context, power, and accountability. This understanding aligns with Edwards’ (2006) critique of allies whose motivations remain centered on self-image, guilt reduction, or moral reassurance, rather than systemic transformation. I am increasingly wary of identifying as an ally, particularly when such identification risks recentralizing dominant voices or turning solidarity into a form of social capital.
I am drawn instead to Vanessa Andreotti’s critique of approaches to social change that seek moral purity or saviorhood. Andreotti (2023) reminds us that “there is no pure or innocent way outside of modernity, no way out — only through,” and that “the desire for purity is itself a modern imprint that needs composting.” From this perspective, allyship is not about achieving innocence, heroism, or moral clarity, but about cultivating an ethic of entangled responsibility, where we acknowledge our implication in historical and structural harm. Rather than aspiring to purity, Andreotti’s work calls for relational accountability—learning to listen, decenter dominant perspectives, redistribute power, and remain accountable to those most affected, even when this process is uncomfortable and unsettles one’s sense of self.
Awareness, Education, and Practice Challenges
One formative experience that shaped my understanding of allyship occurred in 2016, when I worked for Instituto Semear in Brazil, an organization supporting first-generation, low-income university students—many of whom entered higher education through affirmative action policies. I led mentorship programs that paired students from historically oppressed backgrounds with mentors from privileged social classes.
Early in the program, mentors expressed frustration, interpreting mentees’ delayed responses on WhatsApp as laziness or disengagement. Rather than addressing this privately, I facilitated a collective discussion and asked mentees to raise their hands if they had consistent mobile internet access. Fewer than five percent did. This moment reframed the narrative: what had been interpreted as individual failure was revealed as structural constraint. The conversation shifted from blame to awareness, illustrating how easily dominant assumptions obscure material realities.
I also intervened in subtler ways: guiding mentors to reflect on whether meeting locations were accessible by public transportation, and whether upscale venues might create discomfort or exclusion. I facilitated dialogues around meritocracy, revealing how mentors often viewed success as individual achievement, while mentees understood it as contingent on structural opportunity. These conversations were uncomfortable but necessary.
However, I also made mistakes. One early program activity focused on personal finance education, intended to equip mentors to support mentees while providing them the context necessary to understand the mentees’ degree of financial oppression. While valuable for some, it unintentionally pressured others into discussing sensitive topics before trust had been established. In retrospect, this activity should have been optional or preceded by deeper listening. This experience echoes Fair’s (2015) warning—reprinted in Kimmel’s Privilege: A Reader—that good intentions can still reproduce harm when dominant actors control the agenda or pace of engagement .
I also advocated internally for accepting mentees even when scholarships were unavailable, after hearing repeatedly that students valued community and support networks as much as financial aid. Many were navigating university environments where they feared asking questions lest they be perceived as undeserving. After revising the selection process to include questions about the value of participation beyond funding, leadership recognized the importance of relational support. I also intentionally created spaces for mentee-to-mentee connection, recognizing that peer solidarity within oppressed groups often provides forms of care that cross-class mentorship alone cannot.
These experiences reinforced several barriers I continue to work through: my tendency to speak quickly, to problem-solve before fully listening, and, at times, to rely on those from oppressed groups to educate me. While many have been generous and welcoming, this does not absolve me of the responsibility to continue my own education independently—a point emphasized by both Waters (2010) and Edwards (2006).
Taking Action — Allyship as Ongoing Commitment
Over the next three weeks, my concrete action will be to design and propose an intergenerational AI storytelling program for the Palo Alto City Library, building on their explicit call for community partners to "lead workshops" and their recent AI Storytelling 2.0 event, which I attended in January 2025.
Last year in April, I participated in the library's "AI Storytelling 2.0: Reimagining Creativity in 2025" workshop. The room was notably diverse—multiple races and ages were represented—yet no follow-up programming has emerged. The library's website explicitly invites proposals for "hands-on workshops tailored to various skill levels" and "engaging discussion groups that foster collaborative learning." I have both the AI expertise and the tool infrastructure to respond to this invitation.
I will propose a summer Friday afternoon program (leveraging my summer Fridays from work) where families—children and adults together—create stories using recursive.eco, the free AI tool I've been developing specifically to be accessible to everyone, not just white middle-class tech workers. In Palo Alto, an affluent community with significant immigrant populations, many families lack support systems and navigate the weight of their lives in isolation. Public spaces typically separate children's activities from adult activities, reinforcing atomization rather than community.
This program is my attempt at infrastructural allyship—not to immigrant families as passive recipients, but as co-creators of shared cultural production. Creating intergenerational spaces where families produce something together—where children aren't entertained separately while adults socialize elsewhere—is my form of activism against the hyper-individualization that makes autocracy possible. Community is the antidote to autocracy, and creating opportunities for families to collaborate, to bridge the user-builder gap in AI technology, to see their own stories reflected back through tools they help shape—this is how I understand solidarity work.
This project carries risks. Palo Alto is predominantly white and affluent, and I am aware that my own whiteness and class privilege may shape whose families feel welcome. I will need to actively partner with library staff to ensure outreach reaches immigrant communities, non-English-speaking families, and those who may not typically see the library as "for them." I will need to remain accountable to feedback about access barriers—scheduling, language, comfort, assumptions about digital literacy—and adjust accordingly.
Consistent with Waters' (2010) framing, this is allyship as process: action, reflection, correction, and return. My goal is not to be seen as an ally, but to create conditions where families can access tools and spaces that dominant systems have made exclusive, and to do so in ways that foster collective belonging rather than individual achievement.














