Week 2 Reflective Journal: Competence, Entanglement, and Learning to Hold Complexity


Describe the level of competence you feel you have in terms of Anti-Racism, Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion. What has led you to this understanding?
I don't feel competent in Anti-Racism, Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion work yet. I'm at the beginning of understanding how much I don't know. Taking the Sexuality IAT revealed moderate automatic preference for straight people, but what struck me was the physical sensation—my body relaxed pairing "straight" with "good." Wong and Vinsky (2018) helped me understand this isn't just cognitive but embodied: "our embodied sensorimotor patterns...become shared cultural modes of experience to shape our perception" (p. 193). If bias lives in bodies, transformation might require embodied practice alongside awareness.
What experiences have particularly shaped your views of your own culture and the culture of others?
I'm Brazilian and attend Umbanda rituals where transformation happens through embodied spiritual practice. Multiple therapeutic relationships ended when therapists seemed to pathologize my cosmological views. This helped me understand what Chapman and Withers (2019) quote from Ruby Peterson about Indigenous social workers: "the violence of being told we are not professional when we incorporate sacred ceremony into our work" (p. 7). I'm learning that professional boundaries serve important purposes—they protect clients and create ethical accountability. But they're also limited. They can't encompass all ways of knowing or healing.
Another experience that shapes my understanding of entanglement and complicity: my family's nanny in Brazil has worked for my parents for 35 years. Her husband works there too. Their daughter is my parents' goddaughter. When we visit Brazil, my daughter sleeps at their house. They are "somewhat considered family"—except they're profoundly oppressed by race and income. They want to buy a house. My family could potentially buy it for them. I myself could help with the 20% down payment, though it would impact my savings. When I've suggested to my mother that we could at least support the down payment, she becomes nervous. And I don't act.
I tell myself I'm being respectful of the relationship my mother has built with them, that it's not my place to disrupt their ongoing professional arrangement. But the truth is that the relationship IS inherently oppressive—domestic work in Brazil carries the legacy of slavery, structured by race and class in ways I benefit from. Chapman and Withers (2019) ask: "How can we hold our responsibility to challenge capitalism, colonialism...alongside the recognition that we're complicit?" . I don't know. I know the situation is unjust. I know I could act. I don't. I feel very lost about this, and professional social work frameworks don't help me navigate it. This is what I mean when I say I'm implicated—not as abstract theory, but as lived, uncomfortable reality where my privilege is maintained through ongoing relationships I don't know how to transform.
The Impossibility of Neutrality
I'm also grappling with how it's impossible not to let culture influence practice. Doherty (1995) writes about how divorce culture inevitably influences couples therapists even when they claim neutrality—therapists communicate values about marriage and divorce through every intervention they make or withhold. We're not neutral about anything: not divorce, not gender expression, not what constitutes good parenting.
There's a gay couple in our class whose three-year-old wears dresses to school. When I think about working with this family as a social worker, I feel utterly lost and incompetent. It's virtually impossible not to let culture—whether heteronormativity, homonormativity, or ideas about what constitutes good parenting—influence my assessment. If I affirm the child's dress-wearing, am I imposing progressive values about gender fluidity? If I question it, am I imposing conservative values? If I explore the parents' decision-making, am I pathologizing their choices? At three years old, how much agency does the child have?
The NASW Code of Ethics (2021) tells me to respect self-determination and practice with competence, but it doesn't resolve whose self-determination—the parents' or the child's?—or competence according to which framework. I'm not criticizing the Code; I understand it provides necessary ethical boundaries. I'm just recognizing its limits and my own profound uncertainty. Every possible stance I could take is culturally embedded, and I don't know what's "right."
The Mi'kmaw ethic of non-interference—"accept the sincere beliefs of the other individual" (as cited in Chapman & Withers, 2019, p. 17)—offers something about prioritizing relationship and respect. But even this assumes I know what's true, which I often don't.
Learning to Hold Complexity
What I'm learning is that I'm implicated in every relationship I form, and so are my worldviews. My ideas of justice shape every relationship, both implicitly and explicitly. As Ayesha Haq (2017) put it, if we take the side that for women to be liberated, they need to wear fewer clothes, are we oppressing the women who choose to follow their cultural rules? If I lean to the traditional side, am I opressing who feels oppressed by their traditions? Even if I chose “neutrality”, isn’t that a moral stance in itself? I don't have answers. But Johnson's (2023) work on embodied activism gives me hope that transformation happens through how we inhabit our bodies in relationship with others—through presence, not just frameworks.
I'm trying to develop what Andreotti (2014) calls "analeptic thinking"—holding contradictions without resolution. Professional boundaries are necessary AND limited. I need Western training AND other epistemologies matter. I want to help AND I'll cause harm. Economic justice matters AND I protect my savings. I'm learning to sit with not knowing what's "right" in situations like the three-year-old or the nanny relationship, to recognize myself as a limited being naturally implicated in the relationships I form, and to trust that staying present with this complexity is itself part of the work.





